The European Union is the world's largest consumer of food.
The main reason for the rise in inflation in the eurozone was the rapid rise in food prices.
The 13 eurozone countries recorded higher than expected inflation in November, with annual inflation of 3.1% after the 2.6% in October, according to the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts are only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the US, UK and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered its policy rate, as it believes that the lowering of interest rates, the rising commodity prices and the slight decline in unemployment would encourage the emergence of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB is committed to keeping inflation below or at least close to 2%.
One analyst said the ECB was in a bind: it had to "negotiate" inflation to avoid any need for action later.
Germany's inflation rate reached a 12-year high of 3.3 percent in November; in Spain, the rate rose from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
The increase in food and energy prices is responsible for the increase in inflation in the eurozone.
MATIF wheat quotations rose 88 percent, and the price of soybeans also reached a record high since 1973.
Considerable increases in the price of cooking oil and dairy products were also recorded in 2007.
The world market price of crude oil has risen 52 percent this year - last month the price of a barrel of black gold reached nearly $100.
The ECB expects inflation to rise from 2.1% to 2.5% in 2008, but forecasts a decline to 1.9% in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts expect inflation to be 3%, but estimate the annual average rate at 2.1%.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice.
Gallup report on the government crisis
After a long period of stagnation, the number of Fidesz supporters has grown significantly by the beginning of December, with the party having the largest base camp for the first time since 2002, while the support for the Socialists has reached an all-time low of 13 percent, according to Gallup.
The difference between the party-oriented voters is clear thanks to the high determination of the opposition supporters: more than two thirds (71%) support the MSZP compared to one fifth (20%).
The MDF and SZDSZ are, according to the survey, below the parliamentary entry barrier: they account for two per cent of the total population.
