The number of people who still support the government and the head of government after the unrest last October is down from 35% to only 20% today, while the relative majority (33%) see the solution in new elections.
Asked about their interest in the referendum, 60 percent said they would "certainly" participate, and another 20 percent said they would "probably" vote.
For comparison: if the parliamentary elections were held on this Sunday, only 55% would "certainly" go to the polls, another 15% consider their participation "probable".
74% would oppose tuition, 79% would oppose the practice fee, and 84% would oppose the hospital stipend.
The proportion of those who opposed the study, practice and hospital fees would be as high as 81.84% and 89% respectively.
Auchan most expensive, Tesco increased by almost a fifth
The hypermarkets in the Budaörs shopping district have maintained the average price increase of 16% from last year, with the difference that there was no increase in VAT this year.
Articles from Napi Gazdaság
In the Budapest shopping triangle, the price of the Napi Christmas basket has increased by 16 percent this year, but all the hypermarkets have registered price increases of over HUF 1,000.
After the "de-alopement" of food prices last December, the percentage of inflation has not changed drastically compared to the previous high starting point.
However, consumers are certainly discouraged by the fact that what they paid far less than HUF 9 000 for last year is not available this year for even HUF 10 000.
The price of the 'Napi' basket exceeded the HUF 10,000 magic mark by at least HUF 91 in the markets examined.
The highest price was HUF 10.573.
(In 6800 the price was HUF 6800.)
Prices for unicum and live fish remained almost at the same level as in the previous year, but there was a sharp rise in the prices of breast-fed fillets, nuts and poppy.
The prices of flour and bread were in line with the data of the Central Statistical Office of Hungary, but Auchan had 1 kg of bread for 139 forints.
There was no competitive price drop below HUF 200 for the product.
Also surprising was the price of a two-liter bottle of Coca-Cola for under 200 forints, so the drink cost only 257 forints, including the deposit.
However, this year's "Napi" shopping cart comparison showed Auchan as the most expensive and Cora as the least expensive.
Our calculations show that Cora has increased the prices in the "Napi" shopping cart by 15 percent over last year's Christmas prices, while Tesco and Auchan have each increased their prices by 18 percent.
The difference between the cheapest basket of goods of the previous year and the most expensive basket of goods of the current year was 12%, while the increase between the cheapest basket of goods of the previous year and the most expensive basket of goods of the current year was 21%.
The average price increase was HUF 1 480.00.
The average price increase was still 1,206.00 forints in the previous year, but the VAT increase in prices was noticeable at Christmas.
This is precisely the case with trade: it seems that the department stores were not able to decide which price range to apply to each item, since the effects of price increases on consumer behaviour were unpredictable.
(If the trader is not planning the speed of a product, he may lose substantial profits in the price range which depends on the traffic intensity.)
The price of the 'Napi' basket was so drastically increased last year due to the value-added tax that the most expensive basket exceeded the value of 2006 by 1720 forint, while the price difference for the cheapest basket was only 844 forint.
This year, such extremes were not observed, as the most expensive basket costed 1,630.00 forints more than the previous year, and even the cheapest had a price increase of 1,284.00 forints.
Compared to the last two Christmas seasons, the price increase has been catastrophic, with the price of everyday consumer goods in hypermarkets rising by more than 30 percent in less than 20 months.
(This, in turn, does not necessarily confirm the data of the Central Statistical Office of Hungary: for some basic foods, the Statistical Office found an increase in price of more than 30% over a 12-month period.
The same applies to flour and eggs.)
However, if you look at the "Napi" basket, this seems almost impossible, since the price level of the already expensive product has risen by only 10 percent in the worst case, even in the previous year.
The flour suppliers are obviously in a stronger position than the oil suppliers - after all, they were able to pass on the drastic price increase to the multinationals.
In the golden trade triangle, the hypermarkets do not complain; there are constant reports of good years.
Our experience shows that the majority of customers in the three department stores do not even look at the prices anymore.
It is not just the food that is being bought, but also the food that is being sold.
On Wednesday morning, there were endless lines at the checkout counter in all three department stores, when the number of customers suddenly exploded.
However, the country reports lower customer frequency, so many multinationals complain to pollsters that they cannot even achieve the planned turnover, not only in food but also in sustainable consumer goods.
Many places are saving on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand hospital-acquired infections have been reported as a result of improper use of antibiotics.
Hygienic conditions in hospitals, overcrowded beds, overworking staff - all factors that are not exactly conducive to the control of infections, says the chief medical officer of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, too, there are savings in the use of disinfectants.
The trauma department at János Hospital was recently diagnosed with an MRSA infection.
The antibiotic-resistant bacteria was found in a male patient who was admitted to hospital after a serious accident.
The patient has been isolated.
There was a similar infection earlier this year.
The man was released from the hospital after a serious car accident, but he was returned with an MRSA infection, and an important operation has not been performed because of the bacteria still in the patient's body.
As of December 10, 1094 infections caused by multi-drug resistant pathogens have been reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System from hospitals, according to Karolina Böröcz, chief medical officer of the National Epidemiology Center.
So, this is how many multi-drug resistant infections have been reported in hospitals, but the number of cases that have been reported in the dark is likely to be higher.
About two thirds of the infections (683 cases) were caused by MRSA, the methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria is carried in the noses of about one third of the population without causing any disease.
SA-related infections (such as strep throat, tonsillitis, skin infections or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics and are easily curable.
However, if the drugs are overdosed or used improperly, antibiotic-resistant bacteria develop from the well-responsive bacteria and spread rapidly in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
These bacteria can cause serious infections, such as wound infections or blood poisoning, sepsis, particularly in patients with weakened or permanently malfunctioning immune systems, but also in the elderly or low-weight patients.
According to the medical director of the János Hospital, MRSA infection is not unusual, such incidents are part of the hospital's daily routine.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, warned Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA is only absent where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
"These patients are isolated, the nursing staff wear rubber gloves and masks when they provide care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for treatment", says Tibor Nyulasi.
Although patients are tested for MRSA when they are admitted to hospital, infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling too rare
The majority of MRSA-related infections in hospitals are preventable, but the current conditions and circumstances are not conducive to containing the emergence or spread of the multidrug-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection is predominantly found in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine patients who are admitted and isolate MRSA-infected patients immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not so common in Hungarian hospitals.
The reason is that the State Health Insurance Fund does not provide any funding for this study.
Most cases, therefore, would not come to light until the patient had a detectable MRSA infection, says the medical director of the Epidemiology Center.
The European Union has strict recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but Hungary also has guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
Antibiotic therapy is supposed to be targeted, that is, microbiological testing is necessary to prevent resistance to the drug, but hospitals do not always follow this directive.
Among outpatients or patients in primary care, microbiological sampling is even less common, says Karolina Böröcz.
The savings on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most commonly transmitted from one patient to another by healthcare workers.
This is why handwashing, or the wearing of gloves and masks, is of great importance, but there are also significant deficiencies in this area in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but local hospitals are not always able to isolate the infected patient.
In fact, the rooms are often crowded, the beds are close together, even though epidemiologically, there should be at least 1.5 meters between them.
As Karolina Böröcz continues, unfortunately, in hospitals with less financial resources, there are even cases of waste in the use of disinfectants, few nurses, many patients - all factors that can actually contribute to the development of infections.
Such infections are far less frequent, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped, where these protective measures are observed, says Karolina Böröcz.
Government programme against MRSA
MRSA infections are a huge cost to health insurance companies to manage, so they're being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its containment, was included in the government programme.
The programme is showing initial signs of success - published data show a declining trend in MRSA infections in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has identified prevention of the emergence of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and prevention of infections in hospitals as one of its priorities.
The chief of police was not drunk.
In the case of the fatal car accident caused by the police chief of the XXII district, the official opinion is now available.
The now retired police chief of the 22nd district, who killed a pedestrian in a car accident on Tuesday, was neither intoxicated nor under the influence of drugs, said Attila Morvai, the press spokesman for the Budapest High State Prosecutor's Office, on Friday, after the official report on the case was presented.
The report confirmed the findings of the initial investigation, according to which the police chief had not consumed alcohol before he got behind the wheel.
The former police chief, with his own car in the 22nd district, drove into Kossuth Lajos Street, and in the process, he hit a 55-year-old man who was crossing the street at an unmarked point.
(According to the StVO, this is not a mitigating circumstance - the driver has the right to drive, even if pedestrians do not cross the road at the zebra crossing.)
The pedestrian succumbed to his injuries after being admitted to the hospital.
According to police reports, the driver suffered a concussion, then resigned from his duties and asked for retirement.
The Budapest Prosecutor's Office has opened an investigation into the incident.
Moreover, Attila Morvai mentioned that the former police chief had cooperated with the investigators from the beginning.
Another EUR 400 million for infrastructure
Finance Minister János Veres and Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB) Marta Gajecka signed three loan agreements worth a total of EUR 400 million in Budapest on Friday, with the money to be used for education, transport and environmental infrastructure and energy.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved a EUR 300 million facility in 2006 to finance transport and environmental projects implemented with grants from the Cohesion Fund.The loan agreement of EUR 100 million was signed earlier, while the current agreement covers the use of the EUR 200 million loan.
The amount of EUR 150 million agreed in the loan agreement is also to be used for the budgetary financing of education projects.
The EIB has committed a total of EUR 300 million to Hungary for this purpose, with the use of the remaining EUR 150 million to be decided upon later in the context of the extension of the loan agreement.
In the field of innovation, the contract partners have signed an agreement for more than EUR 50 million, which will be mainly used for research and development programmes at the University of Debrecen.
The meeting also discussed the 4 line subway.
It was agreed that once Hungary had clarified the details of the subway financing with the EU, the original contract and any modifications would be discussed again.
According to János Veres, this could be done in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary, with a total value of EUR 8.4 billion.
The interest rates are EURIBOR-linked and the loan is made available by the EIB with a deferral of 8 years, free of commission.
Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is fabulous - all Europe is looking at the once-rarely-mentioned Balkan state.
What, where and who are buying in the EU's cheapest market, which is rapidly becoming more expensive?
The analysis of the Bulgarian Re/Max division.
Bulgaria is currently without doubt the most sought-after place to buy property in Eastern Europe, with cheap ski apartments and houses by the sea.
Among the mountains, the regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are among the most popular, along the sea are Albena, the "Gold Coast", the "Sun Coast", and the historic towns of Sozopol and Nessebar the Renners, but real estate around Kavarna and Balcik is also increasingly in demand.
According to Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria, the interior of the country is also attracting investors sooner or later, e.g. Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, and Triavna, and the very good area of Russe is also seeing more buyers.
The capital Sofia also offers tempting offers - commercial and office space offers the highest returns.
Bulgaria is on its way to becoming one of the most attractive European golfing paradises, attracting tourists in both the summer and winter seasons.
Forward-looking investors are therefore already buying in large numbers, for example around Bansko.
According to analysts, people buying property in Bulgaria also aim to change their lifestyle.
Most of the buyers are English, but there are also interested parties from France, Belgium, Spain, and more and more from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, while the Black Sea and ski areas are dominated by Russian buyers.
There are three groups of foreign buyers, says Georgij Jankov, regional director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle down either buy revitalized properties for 50-100,000 euros, or dilapidated houses for 5-15,000 euros, which they then renovate themselves.
Good connectivity and accessibility, as well as communication opportunities, are highlighted, but proximity to a major city, shops and doctors are also crucial for the buyers.
The second category includes those looking for holiday homes (Bulgaria was listed in December as one of the top ten holiday destinations for Germans).
The third group is made up of businessmen who invest with the aim of achieving medium to long-term value growth.
Real estate in the capital, however, is becoming increasingly expensive, driven by ever-increasing demand.
Although Bulgaria has the lowest real estate prices in the EU, it has seen an annual increase of 21% over the past five years.
The increase in real estate prices far exceeds the increase in wages.
Fodor and the six Hungarian percentages
As Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will be continued by the ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which sets out measures to reduce emissions beyond 2012, when the Kyoto Protocol expires.
There is a heated debate going on between the industrialized and the developing countries.
The US has already indicated that it does not want to negotiate on concrete figures, but it is prepared to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40% by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other big question of the conference is whether the industrialized countries are prepared to support the developing countries both financially and technologically, in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement on assistance to developing countries was also reached.
The Kyoto Protocol Adaptation Fund is to be administered by a 16-member Council, presumably within the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), as indicated in the 'Piac és Profit'.
Unemployment rate
The Minister for the Environment, Mr Gábor Fodor, supported the EU's ambition to maintain its leading role in global climate action and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister stated that the EU would reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (at 1990 levels), regardless of whether the post-2012 agreement is successful or not, and that the Union would even be prepared to commit to a 30% reduction if other major industrial countries and developing countries were also prepared to meet their commitments with strength and responsibility.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the target of the countries that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2%, whereas the EU, with its then 15 Member States, had already committed to a minus of 8%.
The Hungarian target is a 6% reduction in greenhouse gas emissions compared to 1985-87 - a target which the country will certainly meet, according to the press release from the Ministry of the Environment.
The stakes are high in Bali - after all, the long-term international climate agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly not come into force until after 2012 - in which case the Kyoto Protocol reduction targets would not be followed by a new international emission reduction system, the importance of which has also been highlighted by the IPCC, the international scientific committee on climate change awarded the Nobel Peace Prize by the UN in its latest report.
This would delay the emission reduction and would make the increase in the Earth's average temperature by more than 2°C unavoidable, with extremely serious and irreparable consequences, according to scientists.
The British Army is advertising on YouTube
British Army units have posted footage of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan on the video portal to increase popularity.
The British Royal Air Force (RAF) has discovered YouTube: Special Forces based in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, reports the BBC.
The footage, shot with miniature cameras attached to helmets, is checked at Kandahar Air Base and then sent to London, where it is posted on the Internet.
Political message inevitable
Air Force soldiers have already contributed 139 such recordings, their "channel" has been viewed over 75,000 times.
The UK Ministry of Defence was registered under Defenceheadquarters in spring 2007 to publish videos on Iraqi and Afghan operations, but the UK Foreign Office and the International Peace Fighters (MNFI) in Iraq also have their own YouTube channels.
Deployed in Afghanistan
The Air Force originally posted the videos with the goal of recruiting soldiers, and as the Department of Defense says, the posts also serve the purpose of informing the public about the true goals of foreign operations.
Such propaganda is almost free of charge compared to traditional TV ads, according to defence expert Gordon Mackenzie, but the videos always carry a political message, as they validate the military action taken by the government in their own way.
Americans advertise with play
The army also has to fight against amateur images that are uploaded to the Internet alongside carefully edited, censored images - such as those showing the death of soldiers: in the somewhat hypocritical "official" propaganda films, the losses are talked about, but the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
Incidentally, many videos from the Iraq and Afghanistan wars have already been uploaded to the platform, but the British have only recently discovered this "genre" for themselves.
The Americans, however, are advertising in a somewhat different way, with the free-to-download shooter "America's Army", in which the player can assume the role of a soldier in a more or less realistic simulation.
