More and more forces are mobilized for the giant strike
The League of Trade Unions and the Hungarian Federation of Trade Unions will form their coordination committee for the indefinite strike starting on Monday on Friday.
On Saturday, a protest meeting will be held, and on Monday - the day of the referendum on the health insurance law - the work stoppage will begin.
The strike is expected to cause significant disruption to transport, with almost all railway services being shut down, and the Budapest public transport (BKV) will also be on strike until 1 p.m.
Details of the Monday strike will be announced jointly by the League of Trade Unions and the Federation of Trade Unions on Friday afternoon.
A LIGA-MOSZ strike committee is also being set up to coordinate Monday's actions.
On Saturday, a protest rally will be held, and starting Monday, all organizations that have joined the strike will suspend their work indefinitely, unless an agreement is reached with the government.
In other words, the end of the strike, which began on the day of the parliamentary vote on the health insurance law, was not defined.
If the National Council does not approve the health insurance law, the unions will immediately withdraw the call for a strike.
However, if the law is passed, the strike committees meet to discuss the next steps.
Given the agenda of the National Council on Monday, it is even conceivable that the vote on the health insurance law will take place later in the evening, or even at midnight.
The strike, which will begin on Monday, will cause considerable disruption of transport: the railway workers will stop work indefinitely, most public transport will be closed in the morning and more than half of the Volán companies will be closed.
At the same time, there will be one-way highway blockades in many places.
The call for strike action has been followed by many trade unions and civil society organisations - the list of participants is updated on the League's website.
Some organisations announced strikes for an indefinite period, others planned temporary stoppages.
The Hungarian Railways MÁV and the Free Union of Railway Workers VDSZSZ were still unable to reach an agreement on adequate services by Thursday afternoon, despite the fact that more and more people are travelling by train, especially around Christmas.
According to reports so far, the BKV is on strike from the start of work until 1 p.m., at Budapest Airport between 7 and 9 a.m., the LIGA unions for electricity and heat energy are on strike for four hours, and the teachers' union and the Democratic teachers' union have called for 2- and 2-8 hour strikes.
The Hungarian Medical Association stages a nationwide strike at different times, and the EDDSZ, the Democratic Union of Health and Social Workers, a sub-organization of the SZEF, the Forum for Cooperation of Trade Unions, is holding a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four points demanded by the League is that the government withdraw the draft health insurance reform and put forward a new conception for social discourse.
The second requirement concerns the phased introduction of the new pension calculation model, which will be due next year.
The third requirement is that the early retirement scheme should be open to the eligible occupational groups before 2010.
The fourth point is that the VDSZSZ, which is part of the League of Trade Unions, has not accepted the offer made by the Ministry of Transport on the secondary lines and is now calling for a new approach.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard increases state risk
According to the Risk Analysing Division of Political Capital, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, which was founded in August with the support of the "Movement for a Better Hungary", have raised the risk of Hungary and the region in several ways.
The Institute's 'Risk Warning Report' states, among other things, that the highest political risk associated with the activities of the Hungarian Guard is the 'exacerbation of the already existing ethnic tensions between the Gypsy and non-Gypsy population in Hungary, which could even lead to violent ethnic clashes in the short term'.
The main reason for this is the strategy of the Hungarian Guard, which is probably aimed at provoking such a confrontation, according to the research institute.
This is reported as a failure on the part of the political authorities: "public figures have left the discussion of the Roma issue to representatives of radical political groups, who have now based their political strategy on the Roma-Hungarian contrast".
It is suspected that this would exacerbate the problem, make reasonable dialogue impossible, favour extremism, and increase the likelihood of violent conflict.
The research institute also believes that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, not least because of the enormous attention of the domestic and foreign media, have "damaged the image of Hungary abroad, especially in terms of confidence in stability and democratic maturity".
We remember: since autumn 2006 the reorganization of radical and extreme right-wing groups in Hungary has been continuously on the rise, so that since summer 2007 several organizations called "National Self-Defense Association" were founded.
"These groups have in common that they define themselves as a civil organization, while they openly boast of preparing their members for defense tasks (catastrophic protection, national defense, law enforcement), sometimes armed, citing the unfitness of the police, the army, or the state itself", it said.
And further: All this is happening according to the method which attempts to disguise various political aspirations as a civic initiative, based on the political and party loyalty of the population.
The emphasis on the civil character and the association form is therefore not only intended to circumvent legal obstacles that might arise in the course of registration with the courts - it is also a political strategy.
As the analysis shows, the activities of the Hungarian Guard also represent a risky factor for relations with neighbouring states.
"In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been cited in several neighbouring countries as a potential source of danger, with some ultra-nationalist politicians of certain neighbouring countries seeing in the emergence of the Hungarian Guard the confirmation of their own anti-Hungarian policies.
All this has an impact on the political stability of the region", it said.
In the view of the Research Institute, the establishment of the Hungarian Guard is not an isolated phenomenon in Central and Eastern Europe, and the political risk has therefore grown for the whole region.
The Hungarian Guard's activities are reportedly comparable to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, whose creation was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
The background to the emergence of the Bulgarian Guard was the mass Roma riots that took place in a district of Sofia (Krasna Poljana).
The BNU has used the incidents as a reason to establish the National Guard, arguing that the purpose of the organization is "national protection".
In her opinion, the past 17 years have seen a veritable "gypsy terror" in Bulgaria, but the state has remained inactive and indifferent - so Political Capital.
The initiative would have sparked a heated debate in the Bulgarian public.
As mentioned, the increased risk of ethnic clashes is also evidenced by the fact that some Bulgarian Roma organizations have announced the creation of their own guards for resistance purposes.
Since the activities of the Hungarian Guard so far show many similarities to those of the Bulgarian National Guard, it is not excluded that the Hungarian Roma also react to the threats by organizing their own protection, according to the Risk Warning Report by Political Capital.
Attila Juhász, research director at Political Capital, said at the request of the news agency: "Risk analysis is one of the activities of the research institute.
Risk analysis reports would be published annually and, if risk-changing trends are apparent, the public would be informed, as in the case of the risk warning report.
Holidays are not holidays everywhere
In Hungary, holidays are regulated by law, so that the practice of rescheduling working days around holidays has now become established, but next year we will have fewer such days.
The European Union and the United States also have a different understanding of the term "holiday".
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between public holidays and non-working days.
The days of rest are usually religious holidays or are connected with important historical events.
For example, we celebrate the New Year: both the last day of the old year and the first day of the new are days off from work - the latter just so that New Year's celebrants can rest.
In the whole year we have fourteen holidays in all.
The state holidays are March 15, which commemorates the Revolution of 1848, and October 23, the anniversary of the Revolution of 1956.
On August 20th, we celebrate the founding of the state, on May 1st, we celebrate the work, and on November 1st and 2nd, we commemorate our dead.
In addition, there are two holidays each at Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of "work day shifting" has proven to be effective in cases where we would work only one day before or after the holiday.
The price of extended weekends, however, is that we have to work very hard or go to school on the Saturdays before.
The date on which the day of the holiday, which falls before or after the holiday, is finally to be worked off has been fixed for many years by the Minister of Labour in a separate regulation.
The law applies to all employers and employees, as well as to public employees and civil servants.
The only exceptions are those in which the work is carried out without interruption, including holidays.
The only thing that disturbs the working order this year is the holiday season at the end of the year: after 24 December, life in this country is virtually halted, as most people take the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve to make up for lost time, or take the holidays set aside for this purpose.
The next year will have more weekends and holidays, so there will be less change of working days than this year.
The calendar is first "turned upside down" around the working day so that people can stay home for four days in a row.
Saturday, April 26th will be a working day so that Friday, May 2nd can be a day of rest.
The second change is linked to the holiday on 23 October: on Saturday 18 October, work will have to be done before Friday 24 October.
The end of the year will, however, be entirely marked by holidays, as from 24 December everything will be laid to rest, even if New Year's Eve falls on a Wednesday.
Six intimidating little things to annoy coworkers
Emails we forget to send, voice messages we never receive - harmless lies we never notice: they bring "color" to the everyday workplace.
The question is simply whether you get used to these small inconveniences or whether you rise to the challenge and try to avoid these misunderstood, annoying situations.
I'll give you a tip.
"Sorry, I forgot to tell you that someone from the marketing department called", says a colleague.
That you missed a meeting?
At best, you regret it and try to make it up to them, perhaps by calling the marketing department and remorsefully admitting that you forgot to post the message (this is the less common method).
Most of the time, an apology is a done deal.
Before you get into embarrassing excuses, think about how you can make your colleagues feel uncomfortable and try to avoid these situations.
Borrowing something that doesn't belong to you?
There's nothing more nerve-racking than reaching for a document, office supplies, or the phone, and it's not there.
Yesterday the stapler was still on the desk - this morning it's gone?
Or is the lost pen discovered on a colleague's desk?
You should not borrow from your colleagues without asking, for they are rightly upset when they find that something has been taken.
So don't put envelopes or post-its from the office in your pocket, because it might hit you: there's none left if you need it badly.
Gossiping about the private lives of your colleagues?
There is no effective means of stopping a rumor that has already been put out into the world.
Who did what with who?
Where and why?
Information (or assumptions) about the private lives of colleagues should not be passed on to everyone!
And when someone opens up and reveals his innermost secrets, we should not abuse that trust!
It is best to keep silent like a grave rather than to address those who are not present, even if others are aware of the problems of the colleague.
You called in sick for no reason?
If you call the office to report a nagging headache, because you are feeling uncomfortable or just want to rest, you should be aware of one thing: your own work, unforgettable tasks, projects with fixed deadlines must now be completed by colleagues instead of by yourself.
So don't play hard to get with the guys!
If you know the day before that you won't make it to the office the next day, or that something might happen that requires you to stay home, you should report it in time so that neither your colleagues nor your boss will be unexpectedly confronted with the absence.
The whole of the European Union is a single market.
You are absorbed in your work, but are suddenly disturbed by the loud giggling of your female colleagues?
Did you overhear a phone call that you shouldn't have heard?
Do not annoy your colleagues with humming, singing, loud conversations (which you carry over their heads), trampling, constant name-calling or nagging.
All of this can be very distracting, even if they're not really focused on one task (writing, planning, organizing).
Is it always the other guy's fault?
If you have missed a project, forgotten to send an important letter, or forgotten to send important information, do not blame others for your forgetfulness!
If possible, avoid using the office chaos or the noisy colleagues as an excuse!
The best thing to do is to admit your mistake and apologize if it has affected others.
The question of how to make up for the mistake or the oversight is all too appropriate!
At the office - a feeling of home?
Pants and flaps: comfortable for home, but has nothing to lose in the office!
Even then, you should not dress casually, even if the workplace allows it!
Just don't get too sloppy - you should respect your colleagues and yourself to the extent that you dress accordingly in the office - if you want, even pretty and elegant!
