Banks want to deal with crisis
The Federal Reserve of the United States, the European Central Bank and the central banks of Great Britain, Switzerland and Canada have decided to fight together against the crisis in the financial markets.
This will bring more than 100 billion dollars to the currency markets through auctions.
At these auctions, banks auction interest rates at which they are willing to lend money to each other.
For example, the US Federal Reserve is putting $40 billion up for auction, and the European and Swiss central banks are taking another $24 billion.
This is the first time since the 9/11 attacks that national central banks have agreed on such a coordinated approach to defending against or mitigating the effects of a financial crisis.
"This move is designed to address the economy's biggest problem, the growing shortage of available capital that banks can lend", wrote Bernard Baumohl of the Economic Outlook Group, a consulting firm, in a report to his clients.
"The coordinated action of central banks has reduced the probability of a US recession from 65% to about 50%", Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already lost about $60 billion in loans that have not been serviced, especially in the United States.
Analysts are predicting billions more in losses.
"The central banks must have been really afraid of what was to come when they decided to do this", said Kieran Davies, chief economist at ABN Amro.
"It looks like the situation is really bad", he continued.
Central banks are concerned that if banks themselves have difficulty in accessing bonds, their customers will have to pay more for their loans.
That would reduce consumption and plunge the American economy into recession, potentially affecting economic growth around the world.
The central banks have decided to do this after failing to lower the so-called LIBOR, the London interbank rate used for interbank lending.
This means that banks have been constantly afraid to lend money to each other, even though the central banks of the United States, Canada and the United Kingdom have cut their interest rates several times during the autumn.
