Spectacular Repair at the Space Station
Astronaut Scott Parazynski and his fellow crew members on the International Space Station (ISS) spent more than seven hours in space performing the spectacular repair of a faulty solar collector that is essential to the continuing scientific work on the station.
A daring exit that has set several records for its duration, removal of habitable modules, the speed with which it was organized, and the tools "made by hand" by the astronauts to carry out the repair.
The problem arose Wednesday when the astronauts unloaded the Harmony module from the space shuttle Discovery, a large cylindrical piece that will soon be used by European and Japanese science labs.
This module is a sort of landing bridge to the module labs.
But you have to be able to power them.
The crew's second task was to convert a 17.5-ton solar module already on the ISS to its final position.
After moving it, the crew began to rearrange the module's solar panels, which span 250 feet [76 m].
And what happened was that one of the collectors, which are like accordions, got damaged by a cable that was jammed into it, about three feet long.
The restructuring was stopped to prevent further damage to the collector.
The astronauts, who were originally scheduled to leave the space shuttle Discovery for a check-in and then repair another solar collector whose rotation system was faulty, were forced to devote themselves to the damaged collector.
And Scott Parazynski was chosen to walk around the end of the space shuttle's 100-foot-long remote-controlled arm that was attached to the station to perform the repair.
He's one of the best spacewalkers at NASA.
Tall, tough, very skilled, he has a well-developed torso and long arms.
The 46-year-old doctor was therefore chosen to operate on the injured solar collector.
After examining the damage, he cut the faulty wire and attached some kind of rails to the damaged area.
He was assisted by a second spacewalker who remained near the lock, and, from inside, by the other astronauts, among them Peggy Whitson, commander of the crew.
The tool he used, a mini hockey stick wrapped with insulator to prevent an electric shock to the solar panels, which generate several hundred volts, had been devised and "made" by the astronauts on board the station.
When the action was over, Scott Parazynski waited for the collector to fully unfold before he counted his tools and returned to the station.
Yesterday afternoon, the astronauts enjoyed a half-day of relaxation before returning to the space shuttle Discovery today, with seven astronauts expected to return to Earth on Wednesday.
