A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Bad Arolsen Nazi archives, which document the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now open to the public.
The 47 million documents in the archive, which are located in Bad Arolsen, covering a total area of 27 km, could not be accessed until now, except for a "humanitarian" purpose, that is, individually and by name, that is, at the request of a former victim or his relatives.
In May 2006, the 11 countries responsible for its administration - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed to make it available to researchers and historians.
The ratification process of this Decision has been completed and the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The historians' access to Bad Arolsen will allow them to conduct research, 'especially on the deportations of prisoners, the inmates of the concentration camps and the state of health of forced labourers', explains Reto Meistern, head of the archives, which are managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, were opposed to making these name-related documents available to the public because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
For example, the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some deportation victims.
The lists of concentration camp inmates or the arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo were compiled after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians who had been deported or subjected to forced labor and, if necessary, to provide them with evidence of their arrest, thus paving the way for their compensation.
Today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen still deal with tens of thousands of personal requests.
However, some members of the scientific community have shown limited interest in access to Bad Arolsen.
"One should not expect anything fundamentally new in these documents", declared Prof. Wolfgang Benz, head of the Research Centre for Anti-Semitism at the Technical University of Berlin, in 2006.
