The Congress approves the MIFID Directive, which entered into force on 1 November.
In parallel with the parliamentary work, which ended today with the Senate's decision on the amendments to the draft, the Government published the provisions resulting from the new law, with the intention of allowing the entry into force of both regulations by the end of the year.
The representatives of the various companies unanimously praised the efforts of the members of the Congress and the Senate, whose deliberations and votes were aimed at establishing the best possible system guaranteeing the security of investors and regulating the activities of individual entrepreneurs, in order to guarantee an overall efficient market operation.
The MIFID, which redefines the securities regulation, aims, in addition to the modernisation of the financial markets, to improve investor protection, increase the control claim of the Spanish Securities Commission (CNMV) and promote cooperation between the various supervisory authorities of the European Union.
The new directive allows financial advice to be provided to both specialised firms and natural or legal persons and also contributes to the creation of new financial services firms (ESIFs), the advisory firms which merge with investment and securities brokerage companies.
It also extends the number of systems for the execution of financial transactions, adding to the regulated markets for circulation the multilateral securities trading systems and the systems for the internationalization of trading orders, which would eventually enter into competition with the current economic operators.
The law requires investment firms to disclose the focuses of their corporate profile, the nature of the competition and the way in which they deal with risks in the market, and to register all operations carried out, in order to facilitate the CNMV's control task.
The Congressional Budget Committee subsequently proposed further changes, with the decision that securitised debt securities must now be considered "complex" financial assets because of their high risk to the investor being confirmed by the US mortgage and banking crises.
In addition, the Directive on the legal limitation of the fields of work of graduate economists was adopted, 30 years after the 1977 regulation limiting the fields of work reserved for economists.
The Senate also introduced new positions in the financial sector, such as that of an economic intermediary working for another person, who does not need to be authorised by the CNMV and can offer his services to commercialise products and attract clients to several investment firms at the same time.
The Harmonised Index of Consumer Prices (HICP) rose by five tenths in November and now stands at 4.1%.
The indicator used by Eurostat to assess inflation rates within the European Union provides the average price developments in Spain in November.
The publication of this data is in line with the principles of Eurostat and the European Central Bank (ECB), which aim to provide data on the basis of a comparison of location and quality with US products.
The forecast for the indicator can be made in advance by using the same approach as the HICP, but at the same time using various other statistical modelling methods to estimate the information not available at the time of the calculation.
However, the Spanish Statistical Office (INE) warned that the indicator, which was determined in advance, was only indicative and therefore did not have to match the final result, which will be announced on 14 December.
The consumer price index (CPI) will remain at a relatively high level
The Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for Economic Affairs and Finance, Pedro Solbes, said that the increase in the CPI in November was a "temporary development" and that the price index would remain at a "relatively high" level in the coming months.
However, Solbes noted in the halls of the Congress Building that "even if the current figure is not good", Spain's inflation differential with the other members of the monetary union has remained "more or less" the same in recent years.
He also said that November had "fewer surprises" than the previous month, when the government had not expected such a large increase.
