What insurance is best for me?
The insurance of motor vehicles covering a possible accident caused by the driver involves a high cost, the amount of which depends on several factors, including age, sex, date of issue of the driving licence, marital status, type of car to be insured and its use, etc.
Owning a car is just the beginning.
Because it's even harder to find the right car insurance than the right car model.
First of all, we must be clear about what we are dealing with here.
A car insurance policy is an agreement between an insurance company and a policyholder.
This agreement shall be recorded in writing by means of an insurance contract which stipulates that the company shall receive the agreed insurance premium and in return shall be obliged to provide the corresponding indemnity in the event of damage.
The insurance premium is the price of an insurance policy, which is composed of several factors, including age, sex, date of issue of the driving licence, marital status, type of vehicle to be insured or its use.
Insurance companies set their prices according to statistics, so that higher accident risks lead to higher premiums.
This is why both women and those over 25 have to pay less, as statistics show that these groups have a lower accident rate because of their prudence.
The same applies to married people, as statistics and therefore also the opinion of the companies show that they are less likely to be involved in accidents than single people.
The benefits attributed to the vehicle affect the frequency of driving and thus the likelihood of an accident.
The more frequent the use, the more likely the damage.
When calculating the premium, insurance companies have to take into account a number of factors.
For this reason, the driver must also study the situation thoroughly to choose the car insurance that best suits his personal needs.
We have listed the main points to consider when choosing an insurance policy, so that you can make a choice that is not only based on benefits but also on price.
The European Commission has published a new report on the impact of the EU's new policy on young people.
Even if it is best to take out a full cover for ideal cover, there are still cheaper alternatives.
The prudent can opt for a fully insured car with a premium, so that the benefits of a full insurance policy are covered but offered at a low price.
This type of contract requires that the customer pay part of the amount of the damage itself.
'The amount is set before the contract is concluded and is based on the amount of the insurance premium, which is higher the lower the amount to be paid,' explains Luis Noguera, the main representative for Spain at First Europa, an online insurance intermediary.
Another option is extended insurance, which insures the customer against external accident damage but not against damage to his own car.
In addition, this type of insurance would cover theft, fire, and loss of vehicles.
Here's a little advice.
If you are under 25, it is in your power to lower your insurance costs; thus, your credit score will increase as you try to drive safely and avoid accidents.
A credit is a reduction in the basic rate of the corresponding insurance company.
On the contrary, a penalty payment involves an increase in the said tariffs.
'The amount of credits and fines depends on the company and its income.
"If the company has a good year behind it can afford to increase bonus payments", Noguera explains.
Once the 25 year mark is passed, it is easier for drivers to sign a contract, because the accident rate decreases with increasing driving practice.
It is therefore most sensible to opt for a full-cask insurance with a deductible.
'Normally young people cannot benefit from their previous experience, both in the event of an accident and at the time of driving,' explains the Spanish manager of the European company, adding that the majority of accidents occur in the second year of practice, after the 'beginner's fear' has been removed.
However, it is more advisable for a married customer who has no children to take out full-term insurance, provided, of course, that the financial situation of the person concerned allows it.
The insurers consider that couples with children are the customers with the lowest accident rate, and their contribution payments are also correspondingly low.
In this case, a full-cover insurance with a deductible (for an amount of around EUR 300) would be the best option.
'They drive more relaxed overall and have more purchasing power, which allows them to pay a higher contribution', says Luis Noguera.
For pensioners, it is advisable to take out a full-checkout insurance with a personal contribution (for an amount of about 150 euros), or an extended insurance, which only starts with a sufficiently high credit.
Finally, it must be noted that car insurance is a very important thing, not only because it protects the driver from possible accident damage, but also because it involves high costs, requiring a careful choice that is appropriate to our personal situation.
