The climate of Venus may provide a glimpse of the future of the earth
Venus may once have been a pleasant place to live, scientists said yesterday.
Data from a European spacecraft in orbit shows that the planet is even more like Earth's inverted twin than previously thought.
Venus is Earth's closest planetary neighbor.
The two worlds are about the same size and have similar orbits, but Venus is slightly closer to the Sun.
Scientists now believe that billions of years ago, conditions on Venus would have been similar to those on Earth and might even have been habitable.
But because of the unchecked carbon dioxide greenhouse effect, the erosion of the atmosphere by solar radiation and a slower rate of rotation, Venus took a very different course of evolution.
Today, the planet is water-scarce, with a surface temperature hot enough to melt lead, and is ravaged by hurricane-force winds and lightning storms.
The findings of the European Space Agency's Venus Express spacecraft, which has been studying the planet for a year, offer a sobering glimpse of how the Earth might develop in the face of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor of the Department of Physics at the University of Oxford, one of the directors of the Venus Express Mission, said: "It is becoming clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, while the planets are otherwise quite similar".
"Our new data allow us to construct a scenario in which Venus began billions of years ago like Earth, possibly with a habitable environment".
