CNN asked a group of undecided voters to turn on a voting booth when they heard things they liked: The network noticed spikes in approval when candidates spoke harshly about boundaries.
The most intense and longest exchange of the evening was between Rudy Giuliani, the national frontrunner, and Romney, who has pushed ahead in the crucial polls in Iowa and New Hampshire.
Giuliani is trying to shake off the reputation that he was lenient on illegal immigration when he was mayor of New York.
He attacked Romney in his accusation that the former governor of Massachusetts had hired illegal immigrants to work on his home.
The two clashed particularly fiercely when questioners asked whether either candidate would support an "amnesty" (which would give illegals a regular status and the possibility of citizenship).
Less prominent candidates, such as Duncan Hunter, a California congressman, and Tom Tancredo, a Colorado congressman, have been able to get their heads around the issue.
Neither man has a serious shot at the nomination, but both are staying in the race, perhaps because they hit the immigration wall sooner and harder than others.
On immigration, at least, the candidates share broadly the same views: tighter borders, intolerance towards illegal immigrants.
This issue, along with fears about toxic toys from China or other concerns about the rest of the world, helps Republicans forget or minimize the differences between liberals and Christian conservatives.
But the debate was clearly problematic when other issues were brought up.
Mr Giuliani was asked why he had supported gun restrictions in the past.
John McCain and Romney argued whether simulated drowning should be considered torture.
One of the interviewers asked if the candidates believed every word of the Bible.
This led Giuliani to take the position that although the Bible was his favorite book, he might not believe the story of Jonah and the whale literally.
Another asked if Jesus would support the death penalty.
Mike Huckabee - now, contrary to all expectations, in first place in a recent Iowa poll thanks to his longstanding Christian conservatism - said the death penalty is painful but necessary.
When pressed on whether Jesus would endorse them, he laughed and said Jesus was too intelligent to run for political office.
The race remains unusually wide open.
Huckabee's rise in Iowa coincides with Ron Paul's recent fundraising successes and his applause in Wednesday's debate.
These two have come out of nowhere because the two wings of the party have not yet been able to agree on one of the more familiar and traditional candidates.
In 1980 and 2000, one candidate has united the party from the ground up and convincingly with a victorious message of American greatness and a wink to both wings of the party.
This time the party is split and the result is far from clear.
Labour Party pain
Gordon Brown has discovered yet another pit to fall into; his way out of it remains the same.
For British scandals, this one is not particularly slipshod.
No titles of nobility seem to have been sold, no politician's Paris hotel bills paid, no extramarital toes sucked.
But the revelation that a wealthy businessman had hidden donations to Britain's ruling Labour Party of more than £650,000 ($1.3 million) over four years in the name of other people, and that the party had failed to report this, is something that the embattled Gordon Brown would have done well without.
When the Prime Minister two months ago refused to call for an election, foolishly insulting the intelligence of the British people by claiming that opinion polls had not influenced that decision, there was hope that he would deliver a robust, efficient government.
Instead, as Vince Cable, the increasingly astute Liberal Democrat leader of the House of Commons, put it, the once-terrible Brown has gone from Stalin to Mr. Bean.
The clumsy rescue of Northern Rock, a struggling bank, showed regulatory weakness and poor judgment under fire.
The government has been challenged by business associations for poorly thought out proposals to change tax laws.
The tax authorities' loss of personal data of 25 million people revealed unimaginable administrative shenanigans.
A trio of retired generals started a rebellion in the House of Lords in protest against cuts to military spending, claiming that being Minister of the Armed Forces was a part-time job.
Now there are the multiple donations of David Abrahams; Peter Watt, Labour's general secretary (and their former chief executive) has already resigned.
None of this means that Brown is irrevocably headed for resignation.
Still, governments may reach a tipping point after which they feel unable to govern.
Neither do people trust politicians, but they usually hold back their skepticism when a new force takes office.
Once it becomes clear that a prime minister is unlikely to improve the situation, and he doesn't even need to be there for long, that delay is over: the public service starts to leak; the cabinet ministers start to chat; the press looks for bad news; and the government becomes defensive and aimless.
In one way, Brown's position is particularly difficult because, unlike other political leaders, he cannot claim to be a new broom.
As much as he would deny Tony Blair, he was his first lieutenant.
The problems with Northern Rock and the tax jurisdiction papers, for example, are tied to decisions Brown made as Chancellor of the Exchequer.
And even if he wasn't directly involved in Blair's misadventure - as in the long-running "money for titles" investigation of political party funding - voters may assume he was.
Still, Brown's situation is not quite as bad as it looks.
The wrongdoing is not as terrible as the conservatives describe it.
Like Mr. Bean, no one died, or was completely swindled.
And the antidote, painful as it is, is to deliver what Brown's Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable, solid and slightly brutal government.
The new political donation hype is a good example.
The Garbo Abrahams, who compares his donations to his charitable gifts, says he does not want public recognition for his benevolence.
That may be so, but it was not his decision to make.
The laws against anonymity for large political contributors are clear, and they exist for a very clear reason: the public has a right to know who can buy access to those who govern the country.
Watt, who says he knew about Abraham's agreement but didn't say it was illegal, will of course have to ask himself some questions; just like Jon Mendlesohn, Labor's chief treasurer, who was told about the bizarre donations in October.
But so far Brown has not been involved: There is nothing to suggest that he was aware of these confusions, although most of the payments were made after he took office in June.
So far, the Prime Minister has done half the work.
He was quick to condemn the violation of the law by his party, but he watered down that determination by resorting to a familiar instrument, a committee of inquiry on the subject - led to make full measure, by a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, the "learnings to draw" are not very complicated.
If the law has been broken, it's a matter for the police.
Besides that, there are other things Mr. Brown needs to do, such as finding a permanent chairman for the independent Committee on Standards in Public Life, which has been vacant for six months, and moving forward with a sweeping reform of political party funding.
This would require the Labour hardliners to cooperate with the Conservatives and possibly to give up the special financial relationship with the trade unions - bitter pills for a fellow party member like Mr Brown.
But he should be aware of some biased facts.
The Conservatives are now in clear lead in the opinion polls; he has two years to win back voters; and the only way he can achieve victory is through unchallenged integrity and solid competence.
Card sharks
Is the credit crunch infecting the American credit card market?
When blood is in water, it's only natural for the joints of the spine to swirl around in excitement.
Now that the U.S. housing market is in a slump, predators have taken aim at the country's credit card market.
Goldman Sachs analysts estimate that credit card losses could reach $99 billion if the risk of contagion from underfunded credit spreads to other forms of consumer credit.
The signs of tension are clearly visible.
There are increases in both the write-off and default rates, which measure the proportion of loans that are either uncollectable or more than 30 days overdue.
HSBC announced last month that it had taken a $1.4 billion charge charge from its American consumer finance, in part because of the weakness of credit card holders.
It's still too early to panic.
Losses and casualties are still low.
According to Moody's, the third-quarter unemployment rate of 3.89% was almost a full percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be partly explained by technical factors.
A change in US private insolvency laws in 2005 led to an abrupt drop in bankruptcy filings, which in turn account for a large proportion of credit card losses; the number of filings (and thus default fees) would rise again whether or not the general conditions for creditors deteriorate.
The industry also reports solid payment rates, which show how much of their debt consumers pay off each month.
And confidence in credit card-based securities is quite strong, despite the stagnation in other corners of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney of the TowerGroup, a research firm, expects final expenditure volumes for 2007 to be 25% higher than last year.
There are certainly direct infection channels between the mortgage crisis and the credit card market: consumers are more likely to take on credit card debt now that home loans are drying up.
However, card issuers look at cash flow rather than equity, so falling house prices do not necessarily trigger a change in the borrower's creditworthiness.
They can even be of benefit to the map publishers.
The incentives for consumers to continue paying mortgage rates decrease when the properties are less than the value of the loan; as a result, card debt becomes more important among repayment priorities.
Card issuers can also respond much more quickly and flexibly than lenders to the more turbulent conditions by changing interest rates or credit limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risk of a rapid revaluation of assets.
"We're not going to wake up one day and re-evaluate the loans completely", says Gary Perlin, Capital One's chief financial officer.
Even if a sudden crisis of under-coverage in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a lasting downturn are much more real.
If lower house prices and a credit crunch push America into recession, industry will no doubt face a grimmer future.
Keep your eyes peeled for those shark fins.
British bankers plead guilty in Enron case
Three British bankers who were to stand trial for their role in the fraud scheme with Enron's former chief financial officer, Andrew Fastow, changed their plea to guilty on Wednesday.
David Bermingham, Giles Darby and Gary Mulgrew had originally pleaded not guilty to seven counts of fraud by means of telecommunications for allegedly conspiring with Fastow in a secret financial fraud in 2000 to enrich themselves at the expense of their employer.
The proceedings were scheduled for January.
But during a court hearing before U.S. District Judge Ewing Werlein Jr., each pleaded guilty to a case of fraud involving telecommunications equipment.
The three former executives of Greenwich NatWest, a unit of Royal Bank of Scotland Group PLC, became known in the UK during two years of extradition proceedings.
In the United States, her case is the loose end of an investigation that was launched after the collapse of Enron in 2001.
The original charges filed against him in 2002 alerted Fastow that he was the target of a government investigation related to the Enron debacle.
The indictment against the bankers - dubbed the "NatWest Three" - alleges that they came to Houston in 2000 to plot a fraudulent scheme with Fastow and his former top adviser Michael Kopper.
Greenwich Natwest had invested in a subsidiary of a partnership of Enron controlled by Fastow, who was the architect of countless fraudulent Enron schemes that helped to bring the company into the vortex of bankruptcy.
In early 2002, the bank had estimated the value of their stake in the subsidiary at zero, but the three British men knew that it was in fact of considerable value.
A company controlled by Kopper acquired the bank's shares in the subsidiary for $1 million.
The bankers paid Kopper $250,000 for a stake in that company.
According to the indictment, Fastow falsely represented to Enron that the energy company would pay $20 million to Greenwich NatWest for its shares in the subsidiary.
But in fact, the 20 million dollars went to the British bankers, Fastow and others.
The bankers received $7.3 million, while Fastow, Kopper and others stole about $12.3 million, according to the indictment.
In January 2004, Fastow pleaded guilty to two counts of conspiracy for his role in the Enron bankruptcy.
The British trio were arrested three months later.
Fastow is serving a six-year sentence in Louisiana's federal prison.
Kopper is serving a three-year, one-month sentence at a facility in Texarkana.
Each of the three men was released on $1 million bail, which required them to live in the United States pending trial.
Enron, once the nation's seventh largest company, collapsed in bankruptcy in December 2001, after years of accounting tricks could no longer disguise billions in debt or make failing businesses look profitable.
The collapse wiped out thousands of jobs, more than $60 billion in market value and more than $2 billion in pension plans.
Enron founder Kenneth Lay and former CEO Jeffrey Skilling were convicted last year for their roles in the Enron collapse.
Skilling is serving a sentence of more than 24 years.
Lay's convictions for conspiracy, fraud and other charges were overturned after he died of heart disease last year.
Not all the way down to Moscow
The price of a Gulfstream G550 aircraft, equipped with a Rolls-Royce engine and enough range to fly nonstop from Moscow to Los Angeles, is at least $54 million.
But this is small change for some of the rich Russians.
"It has room for up to 18 passengers", said Dan Firer, a Gulfstream representative.
"But none of you are asking for so many seats because it's for a private family or a corporate president".
Firer was at the Gulfstream booth last Friday for the Millionaires' Fair, a four-day orgy of consumerism on display, held in a clustered exhibition center on the outskirts of the capital.
In addition to Gulfstream, more than 200 other luxury suppliers had set up booths, hoping to interest new money-savvy Russians in everything from mahogany-paved yachts to diamond-encrusted car grills that would be appropriate for 50 cents.
Firer carefully took a glowing orange Porsche at the nearest booth.
"It's a nice car, but it's a pittance compared to us", he said.
"After the United States, Russia is the second largest market for private aircraft".
Fueled by an oil boom, the Russian capital seems as awash with money as Dallas was in its heyday.
"We went through the same phase in the 1890s when some Americans came to gigantic wealth and went in droves to Europe, where they were considered materialistic", said Marshall Goldman, a scholar at the Davis Center for Russian and Eurasian Studies at Harvard University.
Like the Saudi Arabian overflyers of the 1970s and the Japanese of the 1990s, the Russians are emerging as the world's most visible and generous money-spenders.
The most exclusive luxury brands are looking for their share of the gold rush.
Elsewhere in Moscow this week, a luxury industry conference attracted Donatella Versace, Tom Ford and Bernard Arnault, the chairman of LVMH, to exchange ideas on how to sell high-priced goods in markets like Russia.
(The conference is organized by The International Herald Tribune, which is owned by the New York Times Company.)
Russia has 53 billionaires who have a combined wealth of $282 billion, according to the Forbes list of richest people.
In addition, 103,000 Russian millionaires are in the second class, worth a total of $670 billion, according to a study of the development of private wealth in the former Soviet Union by economists at the Center for Economic and Financial Research, a think tank here.
(The World Bank says that in 2005, 15.8 percent of Russians lived below the poverty line.)
"There are hundreds of millionaires in Moscow - that's why we're all here", said Nicole Marais, a sales and marketing representative for David Morris, a London jeweller.
She had visited the fair for the first time with the Russian dealer of the brand, the Soho Jewelry Group.
"The women are all well-dressed, and the men are all worth a fortune".
As they stroll through the halls on Sunday night in evening wear, two real estate agents, Evgenia Yumatova, 21, and Svetlana Turovtsova, 26, describe themselves and their clients as millionaires.
"I've been looking at the cars and I'm trying to decide between the Infiniti, the Mercedes and the Porsche", said Ms. Yumatova, who delivered the designer clothes she wore, like a red carpet veteran with Joan Rivers.
The fair seemed to be aimed primarily at the newly rich, the type of brand-conscious Russian shopper who would stand in traffic for hours to visit a sprawling warehouse that shamelessly displayed Cadillac Escalades, platinum pocket knives, Mövenpick ice cream, custom-made billiard tables, Dubai apartments and teddy bears.
The public could buy tickets for 30 euros ($44.57).
"The Russians are interested in learning which brand is the most expensive and the best", said Mr Gijrath, who sat patriotically in front of a large Rembrandt imitation hand-painted blue mosaic stones at a booth at the Dutch porcelain manufacturer Royal Delft.
"Of course, Russians are more interested in Clipper-Clipper".
In fact, the traders here say that the Russians with old money (10 to 15 years old by Russian standards) have already moved from grand logos to the kind of sober brands with limited quantities that would not be marketed at a trade show.
Yet, thousands of people, whether millionaires, envoys of millionaires, or just tourists, crowded the halls every day.
And some of them bought.
On the first night of the show last Thursday, Roman Ershov, the general manager of King Koil Beds here, said he had sold two $70,000 mattress sets made of silk, cashmere and cotton, with sewn threads of gold.
Also on the first night, Mikhail Lyubimov, a sales manager for A1 Moto, a company that provides high-end cars with high-end alarm systems, said that his company had sold the green-orange Porsche to a Russian millionaire for $170,000.
By Sunday afternoon, Andrei Karapetian, president of L.A. Connection, a company that customizes luxury cars, said he had sold three cooling grilles for a Rolls-Royce Phantom that looked like chain-linked arm tires for $55,000 each.
He showed a reporter a car tire designed for a Russian casino owner with spokes that he had coated with colored Swarovski crystals to make it look like a roulette wheel.
The cost: 22,000 dollars for a set of four.
"The Russian millionaire who wants ostrich leather wheels or a picture of his wife's face made of cubic zirconium will not necessarily ride on these wheels", Mr Karapetian said.
"He'll keep it in his 30 or 40 car garage".
Although many of his Russian clients are wealthy, Mr. Karapetian said the phrase "Russian millionaires" wouldn't express much exclusivity at the moment, given the rise in local property prices.
"If you bought an apartment in Moscow three or four years ago, you're probably already a millionaire, at least on paper, if not in cash", he said.
"There are more of them than you think".
Those who were not millionaires could at least pretend to be rich at a booth operated by Alliance Continental, a Russian wealth management company.
The company had set up four red British-style telephone booths, which were stuffed with piles of counterfeit million-dollar bills.
Azad Karryev, the company's marketing director, said his employees printed 500,000 fake banknotes for the millionaire's fair.
Passers-by stopped to toss around the piles of money, cell phone photos as they lean back in the middle of the spare, get a snapshot from friends, or just to put in a few million.
"You see, in Moscow, everyone can feel like a millionaire", said Mr. Karryev.
Suspected botched surgery in New Jersey death
It was the day before Thanksgiving when Ronald Livingston looked out the big glass window of the Just a Little Healthier restaurant here and watched an ambulance pull up on the white Cape Cod two doors down on West Scott Avenue.
Soon there was a police car.
And then there was another one.
"Then I saw the coroner's boxcar coming", Livingston, a restaurant supervisor, said Wednesday.
"That was the point when I knew that someone had died".
The dead woman, the audience learned, was Olga Arroyo, 41, an assistant to the director of the Newark Police Department.
Now investigators are trying to determine if she died because of a procedure performed by an unlicensed cosmetic surgeon, who police have not identified, who worked in the home at 212 West Scott Avenue.
Authorities have not yet determined what caused Ms. Arroyo's death, and are hopeful that toxicology tests, the results of which may not be available for weeks, will help to unravel a mysterious death that sent a grief note through the Newark Police Department's executive branch.
Ms. Arroyo had been an assistant to Police Commissioner Garry F. McCarthy since September 2006, and her voice was known to many in the department.
"She was loyal, hardworking and persistent", Mr. McCarthy said of Mrs. Arroyo in a telephone interview on Wednesday.
"She was my pit bull.
