McCarthy said that Mrs. Arroyo was the wife of Jimmy Arroyo, a former Newark police officer who works for the Alcohol Control Commission, and that she leaves behind two sons, 14 and 11, and a stepdaughter.
Eileen Walsh, a spokeswoman for Union County District Attorney Theodore J. Romankow, said investigators were trying to determine whether Arroyo died as a result of an unapproved surgical procedure.
"That's one of the ways", said Mrs. Walsh.
"It's an ongoing investigation".
Authorities said they arrived at the house at about 3:00 in the afternoon in November.
And they found Mrs. Arroyo on a couch.
She was pronounced dead at the scene.
More than a week has passed and the authorities have said little about their investigation or about the owner of the house, listed as Flor Margarita Castro.
Walsh would not say whether Ms. Castro was questioned by the authorities.
Investigators are trying to determine if any part of the house was used as a medical practice.
On Wednesday, no one answered the door to Mrs. Castro's house, where a withered rose bush stands in the sparse front yard and a Dalmatian barks behind the house.
A blue barrel labeled "Ethyl Vanillin" - used as a substitute for vanilla in food and perfumes - was sitting in the parking lot next to a door that led to the basement.
