"She was always here when I arrived and she was always here when I left.
It was embarrassing".
Hopes that the central bank will cut interest rates lead to the rise of the world stock markets
Stocks jumped on both sides of the Atlantic yesterday after market hopes that the Federal Reserve will try to calm credit markets by further interest rate cuts were reinforced by reassuring comments from the vice chairman of the US Federal Reserve.
Stock markets rose in London, New York and across Europe after Donald Kahn, Ben Bernanke's number two, the head of the central bank, said that policy had to respond "flexibly and pragmatically" to the ongoing pressure on financial markets.
In a clear effort to calm fractious markets in the face of signs of emerging credit stress, Kohn said the recent turmoil had "reversed in part some of the improvements in market functioning from late September and October".
The Commission's proposal to extend the scope of the Directive to include the provision of information on the protection of consumers and businesses against risks of fraud and corruption, was adopted by the Council on 27 June.
The comments were taken by investors as a signal that the central bank is ready to step in and stabilise credit conditions with new capital injections into US markets and possible further rate cuts.
The comments also helped to calm Wall Street in the face of more bad news from the US economy, now that US property sales reached a new record low in October.
The impact of the financial turmoil was underscored by the announcement by investment bank Bear Stearns that it would eliminate 650 jobs, or 4 percent of its global workforce, in a cost-cutting measure to offset heavy losses from its lost bets in the U.S. mortgage lending sector.
Only 20 of these jobs are expected to disappear in London, where the bank employs 1,500 staff.
In New York, the Dow Jones Industrial Average jumped 331 points, or 2.55 percent, to close at 13,289.40, while the broader S&P 500 Index rose 2.65 percent.
In London, the FTSE 100 Index rose 165.5 points, or 2.7 percent, to close at 6,306.2, adding more than 39 billion pounds to the value of British standard securities.
Germany's Dax index rose by 2.6 percent and France's CAC40 rose by 2.3 percent.
The re-emergence of credit pressure on markets was underlined earlier, after strong demand for an auction of three-month European Central Bank guarantees granted to European commercial banks at a whopping 4.7%, the highest rate since April 2001.
Pressure on the Bank of England, the US central bank and the European Central Bank to follow suit and pour more capital into London's money markets increased as credit tensions saw the three-month "Libor" rates for UK banks' lending rise to their highest since late September at 6.59 percent, after a continuous increase since November 21.
