Here are two dilemmas, each almost as difficult as the other.
Who will be the number 6 for England to beat in Kandy this weekend, Owais Shah or Ravi Bopara?
And, no less relevant in a broader context than the first Test against Sri Lanka, who is to make the decision?
The second question is important because David Graveney, the chairman of the elections, is here on call, at least under this particular title, to help head coach Peter Moores and captain Michael Vaughan decide, and because the table of High Morries, the English managing director, is gradually filling up with applications for national electorates, if not for part-time ones.
Whoever doesn't get the sixth-string position will be unhappy, but life is often unfair and sports are no doubt unfair.
It is never easy to pinpoint exactly what enables one person to reach the top of his profession while another never rises above the lowest rank, sometimes for lack of luck rather than ability.
It's not just cricket where the selection is difficult, where judgments are necessary, which are always subjective in the end.
Is it the right time for Bopara to step up?
Is it fair to Shah if he does?
The same question can perhaps be asked in a wider field, whether John Edwards or "Tubby" Banerjee, both intelligent young executives with good degrees who know the business well, should be promoted.
Who can say what the right class is for a cricketer unless he is given the opportunity to swim or to sink.
