I'm inclined to give Bopara his chance now, which doesn't mean Shah might not stand a good chance, if, as the Ceylon teesap suggest, he's the one who's gonna be playing here this weekend.
Buses bring refugees back to work - and to fight Al-Qaeda
The first busloads of Iraqi refugees from Syria arrived in Baghdad yesterday, with a stream of displaced people whose funds or visas have expired and others hoping the city will return to normal.
Some had even returned to fight the rebels they had driven out of their homes.
At the Mansour bus station, even before the arrival of 800 people from Damascus in an official government convoy of a dozen buses, the terminal was busy with refugees from Syria and Jordan returning in private transport.
"I decided to go to Syria after they killed many doctors in Baghdad", said Sabah Al-Qubaisi, a Sunni doctor.
"I came back today because of what I saw on TV and what I read in the newspaper, about what happened in Baghdad and how it would be safe now".
They say the Mahdi army has stopped killing people", he said, referring to the militias of militant cleric Moqtada Al-Sadr, who has ordered his forces to withdraw at this time.
