Small Saarland, good education
The smallest of the Länder is a leader in vocational training and even shines with the international orientation of its universities.
The Saarland is only one of the countries with the same deficit in education as the rest of the country.
"Yesterday I told a non-Islander for the 50th time that we are not French" - this is the slogan the smallest federal state self-ironically put up on its 50th birthday.
France and Luxembourg play a major role in the education system of the Saarland, which is ranked fifth in the Education Monitor of the Institute of German Economics (IW) in Cologne.
The universities have traditionally cooperated closely with neighbouring countries.
The University of Saarbrücken was founded by the French in 1948.
To this day, students can complete their studies with a double or even a triple diploma.
The proportion of foreign students is correspondingly high at 15.6%.
The Saarland also sends a higher number of rural children to higher education than the average, many of them without a high school diploma.
"In the Saarland, the vocational education system is used", says Axel Plünnecke, an education expert at the IW.
