Venus is the infernal twin of Earth.
Despite its hostile atmosphere, Venus is more like Earth than previously thought: The European spacecraft Venus Express has detected lightning in the atmosphere and wind whirlpools at the poles, just as they occur on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have suspected that Venus is a place where lightning strikes.
Now the European probe Venus Express has found evidence of electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: The lightning flashes on Venus shoot from cloud to cloud at an altitude of about 35 miles, reports Christopher Russel of the University of California, Los Angeles, in the science magazine Nature.
According to the famous "original theory", lightning flashes gave rise to life on earth: thunderstorms are said to have triggered reactions in the ocean that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus. "If there was life there, it must have been very early in history", explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there is hardly any life on the surface of Venus. The atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on earth, and temperatures sometimes reach as high as 1,600 degrees Fahrenheit [500°C].
"Venus may be the devil's twin of Earth, but she's a twin", Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and size, has taken on such a completely different development is the fundamental question of the ESA mission.
The launch of Venus Express in November 2005 was a milestone in the history of Venus exploration, as no probe has been sent to the planet since the early 1990s.
The latest research, which is now being presented in several Nature articles, is not only a reminder of the uniqueness of Venus in the solar system, say the researchers.
"They also show that our neighbouring planet has more in common with Earth than previously thought", says the ESA.
So, in addition to the already known North Pole whirlwind, the researchers found a South Pole whirlwind that spins even faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents in the Earth's winter hemisphere, writes a team of researchers led by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second-closest planet in the solar system is almost as massive as the earth and almost as large, with a diameter of 7,800 miles (12,100 km).
The planet, also called the Morning Star or Evening Star, takes about 225 days to orbit the sun.
But it rotates much more slowly around itself, taking 243 Earth days to complete one day on Venus.
Although Venus, with a surface temperature of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, is not much like Earth, scientists believe that the two planets formed under very similar conditions.
On both of them, water accumulated, which remained on Earth in oceans, but on Venus was lost to space.
And while carbon dioxide is fixed in carbonate rocks on Earth, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
