These are not Warhol's boxes.
When you think of Sweden and wooden box, you think of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
At present, Swedish-made wooden boxes cast a dark shadow on Warhol's catalogue of works.
The majority of the 94 Brillo boxes of the 'Stockholm type' listed there are forgeries.
After the Swedish newspaper Expressen raised doubts about the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo boxes a few months ago, internal research at the Moderna Museet in Stockholm has now come to a sobering conclusion: the six Brillo boxes that the former museum director Pontus Hultén bequeathed to the Moderna Museet in 1995 are copies - and probably most of the other hundred or so Brillo boxes from the "Type Stockholm" that are on sale on the international art market.
The prehistory is interlocking, a confusing interlocking of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first Brillo boxes in New York, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the Brillo soap powder cardboard.
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968 - with Warhol's consent - exhibited hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: these did not come from Warhol (for cost reasons), but were delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
They were not works of art, but models of them, mere exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol probably granted permission in 1968 to have a few Brillo wooden boxes produced in Sweden, but not exhibited in the Moderna Museet.
Contemporary witnesses now speak of about fifteen boxes, which at that time were authorized original Andy Warhol-Brillo boxes with the name "Type Stockholm" have rightly entered the history of art and auction.
Some of them have made over $100,000 at auctions.
The problem is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that in 1968 about a hundred wooden boxes were produced and exhibited in Sweden, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén's 105 boxes were not produced until 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By that time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator at the Moderna Museet, has examined not only the six museum-owned Brillo boxes but also three private Swedish boxes, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their press panels were first ground and lubricated, then white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the 1990 copies, on the other hand, shows that the paint was applied directly to the pressed pan without a coating by means of a paint roller - and it is not an oil paint but an acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes", says Moderna Museet director Lars Nittve. "Unless the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York reaches a different conclusion, Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition material".
In July, the Authentication Board announced that it would investigate the "serious allegations" made in connection with the soap-box case.
But since then, the place has been shrouded in unrelenting silence.
