United Internet becomes a major shareholder in Versatel
United Internet has secured a stake of more than 20% in the telecommunications company Versatel.
The average price per share is 14.46 euros, the company said on Wednesday evening.
The company now holds 20.05% of the share capital.
A takeover had been speculated about before.
The option of increasing the proportion of Versatel is still open.
The move is aimed at consolidating the German DSL market, United Internet said.
Earlier on Wednesday, speculation had already arisen about a move after Berenberg Bank increased its stake in the Düsseldorf-based network operator by a further 5% to 15.1%.
The bank only holds the shares for a third party, it was said on the financial market.
The day before, United Internet had already bought a 10% stake in the mobile phone company Drillisch.
As part of a capital increase, Drillisch placed 17.4 million new shares worth EUR 106.4 million.
United Internet bought 5.15 million shares of the company for 31.4 million euros.
In addition, the companies have entered into discussions on marketing cooperation for DSL and mobile products.
"We are strengthening our partnership", a United Internet spokesperson said.
The two companies have set up the joint venture MSP to take over competitor Freenet.
For now, the two companies want to settle for a stake of just over 10 percent in Freenet and not exercise their right to take over another 18.49 percent of Freenet, United Internet said on Thursday.
The two companies, however, remained open to all options, in particular to further increase their stake in Freenet AG.
Talks between United Internet and Freenet on a strategic partnership had been concluded in mid-November.
The poker around Freenet, which has been going on for months and is still difficult to understand, is part of the consolidation of the German telecom market.
At the end of the third quarter, Freenet had 2.9 million mobile subscribers and 1.27 million DSL and full-line subscribers.
The holding company of United Internet and Drillisch held 6.01 percent of the shares of Freenet directly.
It was agreed that Drillish would contribute another four per cent.
The right to buy the 18,49% stake in the investment company Vatas had already been agreed in August.
